INST-8. Decision reference search discipline

INST-8.1. Reference completeness
INST-8.1.1. Cite each architecture or instruction identifier explicitly (for example `ARCH-1.3.4, ARCH-1.3.5, ARCH-1.3.6, ARCH-1.3.7`) instead of collapsing them into ranges such as `ARCH-1.3.4-1.3.7` so `git grep` finds every occurrence unambiguously.
INST-8.1.2. When describing contiguous spans, follow the explicit list with plain language such as "covers ARCH-1.3.4 through ARCH-1.3.7" rather than embedding the range inside the identifier itself.
INST-8.1.3. Break long reference lists onto multiple labeled lines when necessary (`References: ARCH-1.3.4, ARCH-1.3.5` on one line, `References: ARCH-1.3.6, ARCH-1.3.7` on the next) to keep the identifiers readable and individually searchable.

INST-8.2. Reference formatting
INST-8.2.1. Standardise on a `References:` label (for prose) or `// References:` / `# References:` comment (for code) followed by comma-separated identifiers so every artefact has a predictable search target.
INST-8.2.2. Mirror the exact same identifiers in commit messages, task logs, and code comments that implement the decision so `git log --grep` and `git grep` produce consistent results, reinforcing INST-5.6.9 and INST-5.9.1.
INST-8.2.3. When multiple artefacts touch different subsets of decisions, note only the directly applicable identifiers in each place rather than repeating the entire superset; this keeps later searches focused on the precise files that matter.

INST-8.3. Search-first workflow
INST-8.3.1. Before browsing the tree manually, apply the three-step lookup sequence from INST-8.5.1; document unavailable search tools in `.local-system` per INST-2.4 whenever limitations are discovered.
INST-8.3.2. Record the exact search commands in the relevant task log entry whenever the results influence the next action per INST-6.1.3 so future readers can reproduce the lookup verbatim.
INST-8.3.3. Reserve directory browsing for exploratory work when no identifier is yet known, and add a short rationale in the log explaining why search could not be used for that step.

INST-8.4. Tooling helpers
INST-8.4.1. When recurring compound searches emerge (for example needing both instruction and architecture hits), encapsulate them in helper scripts under `tools/`, keep them executable, and document usage in `tools/INDEX` per INST-5.5.3.
INST-8.4.2. Default helper implementations to `git grep` with sensible fallbacks (such as `grep -R` when outside the repository) so they work even on systems without dedicated search binaries.
INST-8.4.3. Update `.local-system` whenever new search tooling becomes available or when limitations (missing binaries, unusual flags) are discovered, ensuring future workers know which commands are reliable.

INST-8.5. Reference verification
INST-8.5.1. When verifying that a cited identifier is discoverable, apply the following ordered lookup sequence: (1) `git grep -n "<IDENTIFIER>"` for committed content; (2) `git grep --cached -n "<IDENTIFIER>"` for staged-but-uncommitted content; (3) `grep -R "<IDENTIFIER>" .` for untracked files.
INST-8.5.2. An identifier found by any step in the sequence satisfies the searchability requirement; record which step succeeded in the task log verification note.
INST-8.5.3. If all three steps return no matches, fix the citation immediately before proceeding and note the correction in the task log.
INST-8.5.4. Do not mark a task complete until every referenced identifier in the affected artefacts passes the searchability check described in INST-8.5.1 through INST-8.5.3.
INST-8.5.5. Note the verification outcome in the task log (for example `References validated per INST-8.5.1`) so the audit trail confirms the search discipline was followed.

